t6500.text: but within the limited frameworks of what we have to work with right now, and with the priority at this point in time being harm reduction, especially in the looming shadow of climate change, i personally think bernie is the right choice.

t6503.text: am i a bernie stan? absolutely not. i’m concerned about his stance on palestine and i’m worried about how much he could get done with a republican senate. he’s also running to lead a violent, imperialist, white supremacist, fascist settler-colonial state.

t6504.text: i just feel that she should be endorsing bernie as his values seem to align closest with hers out of everyone vying for the democratic nomination. i think the priority should be getting trump out of office and getting progressive politics into the white house.

t6505.text: therefore, i’m convinced that warren’s resistance to ending her campaign is a shortsighted attempt at saving face and prioritising personal ambition over the collective wellbeing of her country and the global community.

t6506.text: this ideology does not align with leftist values of equity, justice, and revolution. instead, it seeks to uphold existing systems of violence, oppression, and marginalisation so long as half the oppressors get to be women.

t6507.text: so much of the rhetoric being spewed about her only performing this badly in the primaries as a result of her being a woman seems to be heavily rooted in a white feminist ideology that fails to acknowledge structural axes of power that go deeper than many want to acknowledge.

t6508.text: additionally, she unnecessarily threw punches at bernie during a couple of debates, seemingly prioritising the optics surrounding her as a potential president over the values she allegedly shares with him.

t6509.text: however, when considering her role in the context of us imperialism and neoliberalism as a whole, warren seems much less left-wing than a lot of us had originally given her credit for.

t6510.text: warren, however, lost a lot of respect from me with her entire history with indigenous americans. this was exacerbated when i found out that she was complicit in the us “intervention” in yemen under obama. on the surface, warren ticked so many boxes for many people on the left.

t6511.text: but then it became clear to me that bernie was the more leftist candidate of the two. he was the only candidate that supported prisoners being given the right to vote, he held nothing back when addressing the human rights abuses in india, and he seemed to want structural change.

t6512.text: obviously, neither bernie nor warren are significantly leftist in the grand scheme of things, but many leftists are finding themselves throwing their support behind either of these candidates because of their proximity to and support of progressive politics.

t6513.text: she seemed to have more robust and comprehensive plans that she was planning on implementing should she be elected, and she seemed to, on the surface, be good with lgbtq+ issues and other standard identity politics issues. all of this appealed to me.

t6514.text: so with that being said, is warren’s gender being used as a distraction to capitalise off of feminist rhetoric and shift attention away from the very valid criticism being leveled at her? because at the start of this, i genuinely did want warren to be the next president.

t6515.text: don’t get me wrong, i fully understand that misogyny and the patriarchy is alive and well. however, 2016 proved that the democratic party and the american people were ready for a woman to be president. the dem nomination and the popular vote went to clinton.

t6516.text: on the other hand, so many people keep peddling the idea that if warren was a man, her campaign would be way more successful. is this really the case or is this some last-ditch attempt at virtue signalling her way into the nomination?

t6517.text: like, i’m seeing a lot of discourse about warren shooting the dems in the foot by not pulling out and endorsing bernie, who’s values align closest with her alleged ones, and instead holding onto her own ambition at the expense of successfully getting trump out of the white house.
